{{for|the King of [[Sicyon]]|Messapus (King of Sicyon)}}

'''Messapus''', a character in [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Aeneid]]'', appears in Books VII and IX of the [[Latin]] [[Epic poetry|epic poem]]. He was a famous tamer of horses and king of [[Etruria]], known for being one "whom no one can fell by fire or steel" (Mandelbaum, VII.911-912);<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5Cd-Uct1wIC&lpg=PP1&ots=c59nKJv3vN&dq=ISBN%200553210416&pg=PA183#v=onepage&q&f=false]''. Google Books. Retrieved 27 April 2011.</ref> perhaps because he is a son of [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]]. Although accustomed to peace, in Book VII Messapus joins forces with [[Turnus]] in his battle against [[Aeneas]] and the [[Troy|Trojans]]. In Book IX, which recounts the nighttime raid by [[Nisus and Euryalus]] on the [[Rutuli]]an camp, the battle helmet of Messapus is taken by [[Nisus and Euryalus|Euryalus]]. Light reflected off the stolen helmet, betraying [[Nisus and Euryalus|Euryalus]] to his enemies and leading not only to his own death, but also that of [[Nisus and Euryalus|Nisus]].

==References==
*Mandelbaum, Allen (translator). The Aeneid of Virgil. New York: Bantam Books, 1971. {{ISBN|0-553-21041-6}}.
